{
  "title": "Combining Contextlib and Typing in Production Code (Python 3.12+)",
  "summary": "This explainer demonstrates the effective utilization of the ContextLib and Typing modules to enhance production code by wrapping context managers and type hinting functions for better readability, maintainability, and usability.",
  "key_points": [
    "ContextLib provides decorators that allow for creating custom context managers.",
    "Type hints help improve the readability of your code and can be used with context managers to specify their input and output types.",
    "In Python 3.12+, support has been added for type hinting async context managers.",
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "from typing import AsyncContextManager, ContextManager, Generator, Any\n\nclass MyContextManager(AsyncContextManager):\n    async with suppress(FileNotFoundError) as exc:\n        await some_async_operation()\n\nasync def my_function(arg: str)\n    -> Any:\n    async with MyContextManager():\n        # context manager usage here..."
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "This example utilizes Python 3.12's support for type hinting async context managers.",
    "For Python versions prior to 3.12, the code can be adapted by removing type hints related to async functions and context managers."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "Ensure that you have a clear understanding of contextlib and typing modules before implementing this approach.",
    "Always consider performance implications when using decorators and type hints, especially in critical sections of your code."
  ]
}
